League of Legends Data Analysis

Michael Makogon

May 8, 2018

Setup

knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE)

library(gapminder)
library(tidyverse)
library(rvest)
library(stringr)

# Read in champion id data
champs <- read_csv("champs.csv") %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  select(champion = name, championid = id)

# Read in match data
matches <- read_csv("matches.csv") %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  select(matchid = id, seasonid, duration, version)

# Read in stats data in each data frame, concat them together
stats1 <- read_csv("stats1.csv")
stats2 <- read_csv("stats2.csv")
stats <- rbind(stats1, stats2) %>%
  drop_na()

# Read in match participants data
participants <- read_csv("participants.csv")
# Extrapolate exact position data from role
participants$position[participants$role == "DUO_SUPPORT"] <- "SUPPORT"
participants$position[participants$role == "DUO_CARRY"] <- "CARRY"
participants <- participants %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  # Replace the champion id's with names
  left_join(champs, by = "championid") %>%
  # Get overall match information
  left_join(matches, by = "matchid") %>%
  # Don't need the role since position was extrapolated, and no champion id since champion was added
  select(-role, -championid) %>%
  # Filter out bot lane champs that didn't get assigned the right position
  filter(position != "BOT") %>%
  # Get a more generalized version number, so 
  extract(version, "ver", "^([:digit:]+.[:digit:]+)") %>%
  type_convert(cols(ver = col_double())) %>%
  # Ignore remakes (games less than 4 minutes, with 60 seconds of buffer in case)
  filter(duration > 300)

Game Duration Over Version

participants %>%
  # Divide the many versions into 50 equal blocks
  mutate(game_version = cut(ver, breaks=50)) %>%
  # Get the average duration for each version in seconds, and convert to minutes
  group_by(seasonid, game_version) %>%
  mutate(minutes = (duration / 60)) %>%
  summarize(avg_duration = mean(minutes)) %>%
  # Graph the resulting data with a line of best fit
  ggplot(aes(x = game_version, y = avg_duration, group = 1, color=seasonid)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_line() + 
    geom_smooth(method = "loess") +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.4)) +
    labs(x="Game Version (not patch number)",
         y="Duration (in minutes)",
         title="League of Legends Game Duration over Version")

Flash key over version

participants %>%
  # Divide the many versions into 50 equal blocks
  mutate(game_version = cut(ver, breaks=50)) %>%
  group_by(seasonid, game_version) %>%
  # Only consider participants that actually take flash
  filter(ss1 == 4 | ss2 == 4) %>%
  # Get bool, TRUE if flash is on the D key
  mutate(flash = (ss1 == 4)) %>%
  # Get percentage with flash on D for each version
  summarize(avg_flash = 100 * mean(flash)) %>%
  # Graph the resulting data with a line of best fit
  ggplot(aes(y = avg_flash, x = game_version, group = 1, color = seasonid)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_smooth(method = "loess") +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.4)) +
    labs(x="Game Version (not patch number)",
         y="Percentage with flash on D",
         title="Percentage with Flash on D over version")

Winrate over KDA

# Create a new data frame to calculate kda
kda_stats <- stats

# Treat entities with 0 deaths as 1 for the purpose of KDA calculations
kda_stats$deaths[kda_stats$deaths == 0] <- 1

kda_stats %>%
  # Refactor win from integer (1/0) to boolean (T/F)
  mutate(win = (win == 1)) %>%
  # Calculate kda for each entity
  mutate(kda = (kills + assists)/deaths) %>%
  select(id, win, kda) %>%
  # Join with other stats to remove incalculable values
  right_join(select(participants, id), by = "id") %>%
  # Divide kda range into 25 buckets, scaled to each have the same size, plus one bucket for NA
  mutate(kda_range = cut(kda, breaks=quantile(kda, probs=seq(0,1,len=26), na.rm=TRUE))) %>%
  # Get winrate for each KDA range
  group_by(kda_range) %>%
  summarize(winrate = 100 * mean(win)) %>%
  # Graph the resulting data for each KDA, with a line in between
  ggplot(aes(y = winrate, x = kda_range, color = kda_range, group = 1)) +
    geom_point(na.rm=TRUE) +
    geom_line(na.rm=TRUE) +
    labs(x="KDA Range",
         y="Average Winrate",
         title="Winrate by Kills and Assists per Death (KDA)") +
    # Don't show color guides
    guides(color=FALSE) +
    # Rotate text 90 degrees
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.4))

Winrate over CS/Min

stats %>%
  # Refactor win from integer (1/0) to boolean (T/F)
  mutate(win = (win == 1)) %>%
  # CS = creep score = minions killed
  select(id, win, cs = totminionskilled) %>%
  # Join with participant data to get position
  right_join(participants, by = "id") %>%
  # Only include positions that kill the CS in a lane
  filter(position == "CARRY" | position == "MID" | position == "TOP") %>%
  # Divide CS by duration to get CS/min rate
  mutate(cs = cs/(duration/60)) %>%
  # Divide kda range into 25 buckets, scaled to each have the same size, plus one bucket for NA
  mutate(cs_range = cut(cs, breaks=quantile(cs, probs=seq(0,1,len=26), na.rm=TRUE))) %>%
  # Get winrate for each CS range
  group_by(cs_range) %>%
  summarize(winrate = 100 * mean(win)) %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  # Graph the resulting data for each CS, with a line in between
  ggplot(aes(y = winrate, x = cs_range, color = cs_range, group = 1)) +
    geom_point(na.rm = TRUE) +
    geom_line(na.rm=TRUE) +
    labs(x="CS Range",
         y="Average Winrate",
         title="Winrate by Minions Killed Per Minute (CS/Min)") +
    # Don't show color guides
    guides(color=FALSE) +
    # Rotate text 90 degrees
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.4))

Blue/Red Side Winrate by Champion

winrate_df <- participants %>%
  # Classify participants into teams based off of player number
  mutate(blue_team = (player <= 5)) %>%
  select(id, blue_team, champion) %>%
  # Get participant stats
  left_join(stats, by = "id") %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  mutate(win = (win == 1)) %>%
  # Get winrate for each team
  group_by(blue_team) %>%
  mutate(winrate = mean(win)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  # Center winrate for each team
  mutate(team_winrate = winrate - mean(winrate)) %>%
  select(blue_team, win, team_winrate,champion) %>%
  # Get winrate for each champion and each team
  group_by(blue_team, champion) %>%
  summarize(winrate = mean(win), team_winrate = mean(team_winrate)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(champion) %>%
  # Center winrate for each champion accounting for team winrate
  mutate(z_winrate = winrate - mean(winrate) - team_winrate) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(blue_team == TRUE) %>%
  select(-winrate)

# Get top 10 blue side winrates
high_df <- winrate_df %>%
  arrange(desc(z_winrate)) %>%
  slice(1:10)

# Get bottom 10 blue side winrates
low_df <- winrate_df %>%
  arrange(z_winrate) %>%
  slice(1:10)

# Combine the two data sets
champ_df <- rbind(low_df, high_df)

# Give levels to the factor so that the graph orders the champions based off of winrate
champ_df$champion <- factor(champ_df$champion, levels = champ_df$champion[order(champ_df$z_winrate)])

# Plot the champions their winrates
champ_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = champion, 
             x = z_winrate, 
             color = z_winrate)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x="<<< Better on Red Side                          Better on Blue Side >>>",
       y="Champion",
       title="Blue Side Win Rate on 10 Best and 10 Worst Champions")
